content:
Ending or Inactivating Messaging Sessions Automatically

In certain circumstances, a messaging session's status is updated automatically to Inactive or Ended. Learn when and how these automatic updates occur.

This article applies to: 
Messaging for In-App, Messaging for Web, standard and enhanced WhatsApp, standard and enhanced Facebook Messenger, standard and enhanced SMS, enhanced Apple Messages for Business, and Bring Your Own Channel

Automatically Inactivating Sessions

In Messaging for In-App and Web, you can set a time limit for customer inactivity after which a session's status automatically updates to Inactive. This time begins counting down after the agent's first response to the customer's last message.

Example: If the timeout limit is 5 minutes, and the customer doesn't respond after sending "Hello, were you able to find the ID?", the session status updates to Inactive 5 minutes later.

In Messaging for In-App channels only, if the customer sends a message after a session is inactive, the messaging session status switches to Waiting and the session is routed to your support team according to your routing logic.

Automatically Ending Inactive Sessions

In enhanced Messaging channels and Messaging for In-App and Web, when an agent or automation changes a messaging session's status to Inactive, the session ends 24 to 30 hours later.

Automatically Ending New Sessions

In agent-initiated messaging sessions, if the customer doesn't respond, the session ends approximately 24 hours after the agent's first message (standard channels) or 48 and 54 hours after the agent's first message (enhanced channels).

A session is ended automatically if the customer sends an opt-out keyword in all types of messaging channels.
title: Automatically Ending or Inactivating Messaging Sessions
